04204nam a22005775i 9780520924024DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209240247 a10.1525/97805209240242doi  a(DE-B1597)648451  a(OCoLC)49851975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1995.9.D49bK69 2000eb 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43/62211 aKozloff, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOverhearing Film Dialogue /cSarah Kozloff; ed. by Sarah Kozloff. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (332 p.) :b53 b/w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Study of Filmic Speech -- tPART I GENERAL CHARACTERISTICS -- tONE The Functions of Dialogue in Narrative Film -- tTWO Structural and Stylistic Variables -- tTHREE Integration -- tPART II DIALOGUE AND GENRE -- tIntroduction -- tFOUR Verbal Frontiers: Dialogue in the Western -- tFIVE Word Play: Dialogue in Screwball Comedies -- tSIX Words as Weapons: Dialogue in Gangster Films -- tSEVEN Misunderstandings: Dialogue in Melodramas -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelect Filmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the birth of cinema, film has been lauded as a visual rather than a verbal medium; this sentiment was epitomized by John Ford's assertion in 1964 that, "When a motion picture is at its best, it is long on action and short on dialogue." Little serious work has been done on the subject of film dialogue, yet what characters say and how they say it has been crucial to our experience and understanding of every film since the coming of sound. Through informative discussions of dozens of classic and contemporary films—from Bringing Up Baby to Terms of Endearment, from Stagecoach to Reservoir Dogs--this lively book provides the first full-length study of the use of dialogue in American film.Sarah Kozloff shows why dialogue has been neglected in the analysis of narrative film and uncovers the essential contributions dialogue makes to a film's development and impact. She uses narrative theory and drama theory to analyze the functions that dialogue typically serves in a film.The second part of the book is a comprehensive discussion of the role and nature of dialogue in four film genres: westerns, screwball comedies, gangster films, and melodramas. Focusing on topics such as class and ethnic dialects, censorship, and the effect of dramatic irony, Kozloff provides an illuminating new perspective on film genres.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDialogue in motion pictures. 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aKozloff, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022138340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092402440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520924024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520924024/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles